I have some installation scripts for installing stuff on arch. How do I use pacman so that it doesn't ask users all kinds of 'is it ok to install this shite' type questions. On ubuntu i'd pass -y to apt

Gemini said
Switching from Ubuntu to Arch is a bit like moving from a supervised workshop to a "don't blame us if you cut your finger off" DIY garage. While apt -y is the go-to on Debian-based systems, pacman handles automation slightly differently.

To bypass the confirmation prompts (the "is it ok to install this shite" messages), you have a few options depending on how much "danger" you want to invite.

1. The Standard Way: --noconfirm
This is the direct equivalent to -y. It tells pacman to skip all "Proceed with installation? [Y/n]" prompts and assume the answer is Yes.

Bash
sudo pacman -S --noconfirm <package_name>
Why this might still "break" a script:
Unlike apt, pacman is very vocal about package conflicts or provider choices. If a package has two different providers (e.g., vulkan-driver could be vulkan-intel or vulkan-radeon), --noconfirm will simply pick the first one in the list. This might not be what your users want.

2. The "I Know What I'm Doing" Way: --needed
In a script, you often don't want to re-install something that is already up to date. Adding --needed prevents pacman from re-downloading and re-installing packages that are already present, which makes your script much faster and cleaner.

Bash
sudo pacman -S --noconfirm --needed <package_name>
3. Handling All Prompts (The "Nuclear" Option)
Sometimes --noconfirm isn't enough for complex operations (like deep dependency swaps). If you want to force a "Yes" to absolutely everything, you can pipe the yes command into pacman:

Bash
yes | sudo pacman -S <package_name>
Warning: Use this sparingly. If pacman detects a major file conflict that could break the system, yes will blindly force it through.

Comparison Table
Feature	Ubuntu (apt)	Arch (pacman)
Auto-Yes	-y	--noconfirm
Skip Up-to-date	Default	--needed
Quiet Mode	-qq	-q or --quiet
Force Overwrite	--force (old)	--overwrite '*'
Pro-Tip for Scripts
If you are writing a script for other people, it’s often good practice to run a sync first to ensure the databases are current, otherwise the install might fail with a 404:

Bash
sudo pacman -Sy --noconfirm --needed <package_name>
