Bash
sudo pacman -S --noconfirm --needed --overwrite '*' <package_name>
Note: This is the "sledgehammer" approach. It tells pacman to overwrite any file conflict it finds. Since it’s your machine, you’re the boss.

3. Parallel Downloads (Speed)
If your script installs a lot of packages (Xorg, WM, Fonts, etc.), you can make it fly by enabling parallel downloads. This isn't a command-line flag, but a one-time edit to /etc/pacman.conf.

You can even script the change in your install script using sed:

Bash
