You said
why wouldn't --needed be default ?

Gemini said
It’s a classic "Arch Philosophy" thing. On most other distros, the package manager is designed to be a protective layer; on Arch, it’s designed to be a transparent tool that does exactly what you tell it to do, even if that's redundant.

Here is why --needed isn't the default behavior:

1. Reinstallation as a Repair Tool
In the Arch world, if a package is acting up—maybe a binary got corrupted, a shared library went missing, or you accidentally deleted a /usr/ file—the first step is usually to just reinstall it.

Without --needed (Default): pacman -S screen will pull a fresh copy and overwrite everything, effectively "repairing" the install.

With --needed: Pacman would look at your drive, see that screen is technically "installed," and do absolutely nothing, leaving you with a broken package.

2. Dependency Resolution Logic
Sometimes you might install a "meta-package" or a group (like gnome or base-devel). If you've uninstalled one small part of that group, running the install command again without --needed ensures that every single component of that group is restored to its proper state.

3. The "Explicitly Installed" Flag
Pacman tracks whether you installed a package because you asked for it (explicit) or because another package required it (dependency).
If you run pacman -S <package> on something that is already installed as a dependency, the default behavior upgrades it to "explicitly installed." This prevents it from being swept away later if you run a clean-up command like pacman -Rs. Using --needed can sometimes interfere with this logic depending on the version.

Comparison: How they think
Package Manager	Philosophy	Default Behavior
APT (Ubuntu)	"I will manage the state of your system for you."	Skips if already present.
Pacman (Arch)	"I am a tool. If you tell me to install X, I will install X."	Reinstalls even if present.
Summary for your Rice
Since your rice script is likely running on a fresh install or a system you're actively tweaking, you definitely want --needed. It prevents your script from wasting bandwidth and CPU cycles re-compressing/re-extracting 500MB of packages that are already sitting there perfectly fine.

