Since you’re ricing, you’ll likely be installing and uninstalling stuff constantly to see what looks best. In pacman, there are three "levels" of uninstalling, and using the wrong one will leave your system cluttered with "orphan" dependencies (shite you don't need anymore).

1. The "Standard" Way (The Lazy Way)
This removes the package but leaves all its dependencies behind.

Bash
sudo pacman -R <package_name>
Why this sucks for ricing: If you install a massive desktop environment or a font-heavy terminal like Ghostty and use -R, all those extra libraries and fonts stay on your drive forever.

2. The "Clean" Way (The Pro Way)
This removes the package and any dependencies that aren't being used by other programs. This is what you should use 99% of the time.

Bash
sudo pacman -Rs <package_name>
R: Remove

s: Recursive (nuke the unused dependencies too)

3. The "Nuclear" Way (The Rice-Reset)
If you want to remove the package, its dependencies, and the configuration files it created in system directories:

Bash
sudo pacman -Rns <package_name>
n: Nosave (ignores the .pacsave backup files pacman usually creates)

4. How to Automation-Proof it (No Prompts)
Just like with installation, if you want your script to just "make it go away" without asking for permission:

Bash
sudo pacman -Rns --noconfirm <package_name>
Pro-Tip: Cleaning up the "Leftovers"
If you’ve been experimenting and realize you have a bunch of "orphans" (packages installed as dependencies that are no longer needed by anything), run this magic command:

Bash
sudo pacman -Rs $(pacman -Qdtq)
What that does:
pacman -Qdtq: Lists all Queried packages that are dependencies, terminal (not required by anything else), and quiet (just the names).

pacman -Rs: Feeds that list into the remove command.

Wait! One quick warning: pacman will never touch the files in your /home/user directory (like your .config/ghostty folder). You’ll have to rm -rf those manually if you want a truly clean slate for your rice.

